Welcome to the=C2=A0579=C2=A0newly Not Boring people=C2=A0who have joined u=
s since last Tuesday! If you haven=E2=80=99t subscribed, join=C2=A0208,497 =
smart, curious folks by subscribing here:=20
Today=E2=80=99s Not Boring is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Slack [ https://li=
nk.sbstck.com/redirect/1b609e49-7cf9-4eb5-97f2-0c05c3ee322a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]
What=E2=80=99s the first thing founders do when starting a company? Buy a w=
ebsite domain? File incorporation docs? Add =E2=80=9CStealth=E2=80=9D to th=
eir LinkedIn?
Nope. The first thing founders do is start a new Slack Workspace [ https://=
link.sbstck.com/redirect/1b609e49-7cf9-4eb5-97f2-0c05c3ee322a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Why? Because Slack [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/1b609e49-7cf9-4eb5-97=
f2-0c05c3ee322a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ] is where thoughtful work gets done quickly.
Slack [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/1b609e49-7cf9-4eb5-97f2-0c05c3ee32=
2a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] sen=
t us a bunch of ad copy to include here, but this is a product I know and u=
se every single day so I=E2=80=99m going to tell you why I like the product=
=2E
Partner Management. You know when you have a longstanding partner =E2=80=93=
 it could be an agency, consultant, supplier =E2=80=93 and you have dozens =
of poorly labeled emails threads going with them? Yeah, just skip all of th=
at and get your closest partners added to your Slack channel, either as a m=
ember or via Connect.
Find what you need, share what you know. From files to photos to conversati=
ons, everyone can access any message that=E2=80=99s ever been shared in pub=
lic channels, so they have all the information they need to make decisions =
and move work forward. Crtl+f makes the world go round.
Connect instantly with huddles. Fun fact, Dan and I have never scheduled a =
video meeting. But we huddle all the time. With huddles you can talk, video=
 chat, or share your screen instantly with anyone in your Slack.
Right now, you can save 50% off your first 3 months of Slack Pro [ https://=
link.sbstck.com/redirect/1b609e49-7cf9-4eb5-97f2-0c05c3ee322a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiO=
XAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ].
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,=C2=A0
Happy Tuesday!=C2=A0
Last week, we talked about moats [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/7d6cba4=
9-0489-4d74-af64-2f5664614fce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] and uncertainty.=C2=A0
The takeaway from that one is that, =E2=80=9CNew startups have a limited wi=
ndow of time during which they=E2=80=99re protected by the cover of uncerta=
inty to dig moats, and if they don=E2=80=99t dig them by the time others ca=
tch on, their excess profit will be competed away and they=E2=80=99ll strug=
gle to achieve a good outcome.=E2=80=9D
At the end, I left you with a little cliffhanger. I said we were going to t=
alk about strategy.=C2=A0
So this week, we=E2=80=99re going to talk about strategy.
Let=E2=80=99s get to it.
In Defense of Strategy
There=E2=80=99s a belief in tech that execution is all that matters, that s=
trategy is for wimpy MBAs.=C2=A0
That belief is wrong, and I have the scars to prove it.=C2=A0
Before Not Boring, I worked at a flexible workspace startup called Breather=
=2E I=E2=80=99ve written about my time the=
re before [ https://link.sbstck.com=
/redirect/6172db6d-a862-4241-a22e-dccc91cc70a3?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5=
T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. We ran a well-oiled machine acros=
s 500 spaces in 10 markets with bookings by the hour, non-stop operations, =
the best tech in the industry, and an NPS consistently in the 70s and 80s. =
We were great at some things and bad at other things, but one thing was und=
eniable: we could fucking execute.
And yet, we failed. After raising $120 million, we sold for $3 million in 2=
021. What killed Breather wasn=E2=80=99t a lack of execution. It was bad st=
rategy.=C2=A0
Execution without strategy is wasteful and tragic. Just as =E2=80=9CCompani=
es that have the best products, most talented people, and fastest growth ar=
e precisely the ones for which moats are most important,=E2=80=9D companies=
 that are the best at execution are precisely the ones for which strategy i=
s most important. They=E2=80=99re the only ones that have a shot.=C2=A0
The better you are at execution, the faster you can run in any direction. A=
 good strategy helps you run fast in the right direction.=C2=A0
Execution is necessary but not sufficient. Strategy isn=E2=80=99t sufficien=
t either, but it is necessary.=C2=A0
For some reason, though, it=E2=80=99s a badge of honor in tech to shit on s=
trategy.=C2=A0
Well, I am here to defend strategy.=C2=A0
Strategy is the difference between playing startup and building an enduring=
 business. I=E2=80=99ve racked my brain (and Google, and ChatGPT) for examp=
les of startups that have achieved $10 billion+ outcomes without a good str=
ategy, without moats in place by the time their success became obvious, and=
 I just can=E2=80=99t come up with any.=C2=A0=C2=A0
If startups need to dig moats before their uncertainty runs out, strategy i=
s how they do it. If moats are the what, strategy is the how.=C2=A0
Every startup has a window of time during which they must simultaneously bu=
ild something worth defending and build defenses around it.=C2=A0
For new startups, strategy is deciding how to use the window wisely. It=E2=
=80=99s about directing your limited resources towards digging moats before=
 you=E2=80=99ve removed enough uncertainty to attract serious competition.
Like moats, strategy is often thought of as something that bigger companies=
 need to worry about, when they have to coordinate thousands of people and =
defend against dozens of competitors. Most of the strategy literature is wr=
itten for those bigger companies, and most of it is overkill for startups.=
=C2=A0
That doesn=E2=80=99t mean that strategy is more important for big companies=
 than for startups. The opposite is true: strategy is highest-leverage at D=
ay 0, when all paths are available.=C2=A0
I made strategy look too clean in that graphic. Under conditions of uncerta=
inty, your strategy will need to change as you learn and as the situation e=
volves.=C2=A0
But crafting a strategy upfront lets you throw all of your limited resource=
s in one direction from the start, build the strengths you need to win in t=
he market you=E2=80=99ve chosen, and hopefully, if things go just right, co=
mpound all the little actions you take in the course of building your busin=
ess into something real and defensible by the time your uncertainty window =
closes.=C2=A0
If you use the uncertainty window to execute blindly for a while before cra=
fting a strategy, you=E2=80=99ve both wasted precious uncertainty time and =
made decisions =E2=80=93 hired people, signed customers, taken on outside c=
apital =E2=80=93 that will make it harder to change direction when you deci=
de you must.
This all seems kind of tautological. Few would disagree that it=E2=80=99s b=
etter to execute in a direction than not. And done right, that=E2=80=99s wh=
at strategy helps do.=C2=A0
So why does strategy get such a bad rap?=C2=A0
Bad Strategy
Most capital-S Strategy, as it=E2=80=99s taught and practiced by people who=
 call it Strategy, is Bad Strategy.=C2=A0
When Ben Rollert [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/0c03fcbe-6860-409b-b5a0=
-4be69d716f2a?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ] and I told Breather=E2=80=99s exec team that we were going to spend=
