Good Startup Strategy
Rumelt doesn=E2=80=99t give a one-sentence definition of strategy in the bo=
ok, but if he did, it would look something like this:=C2=A0
A strategy is a high-level plan to achieve one or more goals under conditio=
ns of uncertainty, designed through recognizing the challenge (diagnosis), =
setting a direction to overcome it (guiding policy), and detailing steps to=
 implement the policy (coherent actions).=C2=A0
Those three pieces =E2=80=94 diagnosis, guiding policy, and coherent action=
s =E2=80=94 form the strategy kernel. By combining the strategy kernel with=
 what we discussed in When to Dig a Moat [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect=
/7d6cba49-0489-4d74-af64-2f5664614fce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlN=
uaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], we can come up with something a little mor=
e tailored to early stage startups.
A startup can=E2=80=99t be expected to have moats in the early days, but it=
 should have a strategy in place that gives it the best chance of having th=
em in place by the time the uncertainty window runs out.=C2=A0
The best time to craft a strategy is before you start the company; the seco=
nd best time is now.=C2=A0
Strategy isn=E2=80=99t set in stone. It should evolve as the facts do, and =
as the startup learns by doing. A startup=E2=80=99s strategy should actuall=
y evolve faster than a larger company=E2=80=99s because there=E2=80=99s so =
much uncertainty and such a high rate of learning, and because a startup is=
 still nimble enough to change course as needed.=C2=A0
A rough way of thinking about what should change is that the diagnosis shou=
ld be the most stable, the guiding policy should be relatively stable, and =
the coherent actions should be the quickest to adapt to new information. Le=
t=E2=80=99s take each in turn.=C2=A0
Diagnosis
At a minimum, a diagnosis names or classifies the situation, linking facts =
into patterns and suggesting more attention be paid to some issues and less=
 to others.
A good diagnosis is the most important piece of the strategy kernel for a s=
tartup. Getting it right is the highest leverage thing you can do, so we=E2=
=80=99ll spend most of our time here.=C2=A0
Every founder does some form of diagnosis before starting a company. They s=
urvey the landscape of available products and unmet customer needs, and eva=
luate their own abilities and the inputs available to build a better soluti=
on.=C2=A0
This shows up in pitch decks as the =E2=80=9CProblem=E2=80=9D and =E2=80=9C=
Solution=E2=80=9D slides, and in investor conversations as the answer to =
=E2=80=9CWhy now?=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
My brother Dan started Create [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/821d8366-9=
6df-4b4e-b1c6-fee93248cb7f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXep=
KbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ] because he noticed a wide gap between the public perce=
ption of creatine and the very positive research on its effectiveness, real=
ized that well-branded gummies would be a more palatable form factor than p=
owders for most consumers, and recognized that his experience at Away, Para=
de, and Not Boring gave him the right skillset to build the brand. A little=
 over six months in, he=E2=80=99s at a $6 million run rate. It seems to hav=
e been a good diagnosis.=C2=A0
Most startups stop there, but a good startup diagnosis needs to go further.=
=C2=A0
First, startups need to honestly assess how obvious their product is and ho=
w hard it is to build.=C2=A0
This is what we talked about in When to Dig a Moat [ https://link.sbstck.co=
m/redirect/7d6cba49-0489-4d74-af64-2f5664614fce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J=
5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ]. Estimate a starting uncertainty =
window, a rough guide for how soon you=E2=80=99ll face competition, how qui=
ckly you=E2=80=99ll need to dig moats, and how deep they=E2=80=99ll need to=
 be.
Because the uncertainty window depends on the progress a company makes, it=
=E2=80=99s more useful to think about this in terms of milestones than time=
: =E2=80=9CBy the time we=E2=80=99ve proven X, competitors are likely to at=
tack.=E2=80=9D That=E2=80=99s when you should have early moats in place.=C2=
=A0
Then, startups need to understand which moats, which of Hamilton Helmer=E2=
=80=99s 7 Powers [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2a10f313-693f-439e-a057=
-28aaff0bf701?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8Ex=
kRNpU ], are available in the market they=E2=80=99re attacking.=C2=A0
Picking the right moat for your market is crucial.
As Dan Hockenmaier [ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2c98c9ff-976c-47e3-83=
a6-d52a8b776798?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8=
ExkRNpU ], who runs strategy and analytics at Faire [ https://www.faire.com=
/ ] put it: =E2=80=9CMost of the value is picking a lane that=E2=80=99s goi=
ng to lend itself to defensibility.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
If you=E2=80=99re building a physical product, you might focus on scale eco=
nomies. If you=E2=80=99re building a SaaS product, you might focus on switc=
hing costs. If you=E2=80=99re building a social app, you=E2=80=99ll probabl=
y focus on network effects.
It=E2=80=99s important to be a student of history here. Optimism is an impo=
rtant trait in a founder, but realism skewing towards pessimism is the righ=
t state of mind for a diagnosis. The first moat you reach for might not sur=
vive deeper scrutiny.
Take social apps. Understand why the last 1,000 failed before convincing yo=
urself you=E2=80=99ll be the one to crack network effects.=20
Or marketplaces. Hockenmaier notes that, =E2=80=9CNetwork effects are overr=
ated for marketplaces. They are usually not enough to drive defensibility o=
n their own. They take too many lessons from single-sided network effects a=
nd ignore the challenges with dual-sided networks.=E2=80=9D Look instead to=
 scale economies or switching costs.
Aim for moats with non-linear returns, where being 2x or 10x bigger provide=
s outsized benefits. Hockenmaier looks for =E2=80=9Casymptoting curves that=
 take a long time to asymptote.=E2=80=9D The goal is finding moats where yo=
u stay steps ahead thanks to non-linear returns.=C2=A0
Airbnb picked the right asymptoting curves =E2=80=93 more supply kept deliv=
ering more defensibility. When Wimdu tried to compete with it in Europe, Ai=
rbnb won because its scale drove cross-border network effects. Airbnb picke=
d a business in which getting to scale fast mattered, and then got to scale=
 fast before the window closed.
Looking for curves that take a long time to asymptote is a good rule of thu=
mb when evaluating network effects, switching costs, and scale economies in=
 any industry: once you=E2=80=99re running in the right direction, how far =
can out-executing your competitors take you?=C2=A0
No matter which industry you=E2=80=99re entering, if you get to this point =
in the diagnosis and the best potential moat you can come up with is brand =
or process power, you might be in trouble. Both take a very long time to de=
velop, if they do at all, and when they do, it=E2=80=99s often through some=
 emergent magic.=C2=A0
Cornered resources are also tricky, but not impossible, to acquire.=20
So before you launch, and definitely before you raise money, figure out whe=
ther you think you can create scale economies, switching costs, maybe netwo=
rk effects, or mayyybe cornered resources before your uncertainty window cl=
oses.=C2=A0
But what if that=E2=80=99s not enough time? What if you=E2=80=99re entering=
 a market that already has competitors?=C2=A0
My favorite power =E2=80=93 counter-positioning =E2=80=93 might be able to =
help. Counter-positioning isn=E2=80=99t a forever moat, but it can be reall=
y useful in extending your window until you can dig one.=C2=A0Ramp [ https:=
//ramp.com/ ] counter-positioned beautifully in corporate cards. I wrote ab=
out it here [ https://www.notboring.co/p/ramp-the-card-sized-finance-team ]=
 and here [ https://www.notboring.co/p/ramping-up ].
Not every idea has a viable path to defensibility. That=E2=80=99s OK. It=E2=
=80=99s better to toss the idea or decide to bootstrap after a couple weeks=
 of researching and writing than it is to spend years of your life and mill=
ions of dollars of other peoples=E2=80=99 money going the venture-backed ro=
ute on something that you know ahead of time will probably fail.=20
Knowing what game you should be playing is strategy, too.=C2=A0
Finally, if the founders see a path to defensibility, they need to determin=
e the one or two most important challenges to address head-on.=C2=A0
Based on your diagnosis, what is the most critical solvable problem facing =
your company? Identify that upfront, and craft your strategy around solving=
 it.=C2=A0
These will be different for every business and every industry. In The Crux =
[ https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/17f9ea38-dc15-4761-a507-66042a19d4d3?j=
=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], Rumelt=
 talks about Elon Musk realizing that launches were too expensive to ever g=
et humans to Mars, identifying reusability as the most important issue to s=
olve for affordability, and throwing all of his early resources at reusabil=
ity.=C2=A0
Sometimes, the challenge will be so big that it=E2=80=99s worth throwing ev=
erything at solving it before worrying about anything else. SpaceX didn=E2=
=80=99t develop Starlink, which gives it unbeatable  [ https://caseyhandmer=
=2Ewordpress.com/2019/11/02/starlink-is=
-a-very-big-deal/ ]scale economies [ h=
ttps://caseyhandmer.wordpress.com/2019/11/02/starlink-is-a-very-big-deal/ ]=
, until a decade into the company=E2=80=99s life. The uncertainty and diffi=
culty of its rocket capabilities gave it a big enough headstart that it did=
n=E2=80=99t need to worry about long-term moats too early.=C2=A0
Often, though, it=E2=80=99s useful to identify two challenges to start atta=
cking immediately:
The thing you need to prove to reduce uncertainty (novel or complexity).=C2=
=A0
The path to defensibility.=C2=A0
With that, you=E2=80=99ve completed the diagnosis. You understand the compe=
titive landscape, the why now, roughly how long of an uncertainty window yo=
u=E2=80=99ll have, which moats you need to have in place when it runs out, =
and the couple of core challenges you=E2=80=99ll need to address.=C2=A0
It might seem like a lot, but at the end of the diagnosis, you=E2=80=99ve s=
anity-checked your idea and simplified a ton of complexity into just a coup=
le of obstacles to overcome. Now it=E2=80=99s time to translate that work i=
nto decisions about how your company will operate.=C2=A0
Guiding Policy=C2=A0
The guiding policy outlines an overall approach for overcoming the obstacle=
s highlighted by the diagnosis. It is =E2=80=98guiding=E2=80=99 because it =
channels action in certain directions without defining exactly what should =
be done.
A good guiding policy flows from the diagnosis: it=E2=80=99s where you figu=
re out how to overcome the obstacles you=E2=80=99ve identified =E2=80=9Cby =
creating or drawing upon sources of advantage.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
A lot of the things that startups think that they need instead of a strateg=
y are actually just the guiding policy. If a startup=E2=80=99s advantage is=
 that it can ship faster than incumbents, speed can be a part of the guidin=
g policy. If its advantage is that it can target a growing niche too small =
for an incumbent to care about and ride it to greatness, like Stripe did wi=
th startup developers, focusing on that niche at the expense of other oppor=
tunities can be part of the guiding policy.=C2=A0
Startups come pre-loaded with very few strengths. There are the generic one=
s, like speed and focus, and whatever strengths the founders bring with the=
m, but for the most part, they=E2=80=99re blank slates. The beauty of the g=
uiding policy for startups is that they=E2=80=99re free to choose which str=
engths they want to develop based on the diagnosis.=C2=A0
Varda, which I wrote about in June [ https://www.notboring.co/p/varda-the-s=
pace-drug-factory ], is a beautiful example of a diagnosis informing a guid=
ing policy with an eye towards defensibility.=C2=A0
Delian Asparouhov [ https://twitter.com/zebulgar ] started Varda after real=
izing declining launch costs could make space manufacturing economics work.
His diagnosis: Varda needed to excel at manufacturing, returning payloads, =
and selling. Focusing on both commercial and government customers could hel=
p it gain advantages and develop scale economies.
Varda's guiding policy flowed directly from this diagnosis:
Brought on experts in those 3 areas: Will Bruey for reentry, Adrian Radocea=
 for manufacturing, Eric Lasker for sales.
Prioritized speed with experienced hires =E2=80=94 =E2=80=9Cthe trains run =
on time=E2=80=9D
Focused on both DoD and pharma clients to kickstart a flywheel. DoD ridesha=
res lower costs for pharma. More pharma demand enables cheaper DoD rides. L=
ower prices drive more volume and integration, further reducing costs.
The beauty of Varda=E2=80=99s strategy is how focused and aligned everythin=
g is: get to scale faster than anyone else to drive down costs. Varda doesn=
=E2=80=99t have moats yet, but with everything it does in the course of ope=
rating its business, it=E2=80=99s digging them.=C2=A0
Coherent Actions=C2=A0
Strategy is about action, about doing something=E2=80=A6 The actions within=
 the kernel of strategy should be coherent. That is, the resource deploymen=
ts, policies, and maneuvers that are undertaken should be consistent and co=
ordinated. The coordination of action provides the most basic source of lev=
erage or advantage available in strategy.=C2=A0
Every startup has limited resources. It can only spend so much money, hire =
so many people, and take so many actions before the money runs out.=C2=A0
A good diagnosis and guiding policy channels and coordinates those limited =
actions so that they can compound on each other.
Good strategy can actually free startups up to move faster by making it cle=
ar exactly what the company wants to do, and for whom, and giving autonomy =
to the talented people it hires by letting them select their own coherent a=
ctions that fit within the strategy. A clear strategy from the top allows m=
ore independent decision-making at all levels.=C2=A0
This, finally, is where execution comes into play. Execution absolutely mat=
ters, but it=E2=80=99s only effective if it=E2=80=99s guided in such a way =
that it addresses the one or two things that remove uncertainty and defend =
the business once the uncertainty is removed.=C2=A0
I planned to spend most of the essay on coherent actions, on the idea that =
they=E2=80=99re the equivalent of compound interest for startups, but once =
I started writing, I realized that if you get the diagnosis and guiding pol=
icy right, coherent actions flow in the course of execution. And coherent a=
ctions=20
So I=E2=80=99ll show you how it worked at Breather instead.=C2=A0
Good Strategy at Breather
Diagnosis
In late 2017, Breather operated roughly 400 spaces in ten markets after exp=
anding way too quickly based on incorrectly analogizing ourselves to Uber (=
every startup=E2=80=99s strategy is unique!). We set a goal to add a space =
every day, and we did it, even if it meant adding spaces that weren=E2=80=
=99t ideal. That left us with too many spaces that didn=E2=80=99t fill up a=
nd lost money. As a result, our gross margins across the network sat at -25=
%.=C2=A0
At the time, we only let customers book hourly bookings up to a full day th=
rough our app. Customers were asking us if they could rent spaces for longe=
r periods =E2=80=93 a month or more =E2=80=93 but we told them that=E2=80=
=99s not what we do. Better-funded competitors like WeWork and Knotel focus=
ed exclusively on these relatively longer bookings, and we didn=E2=80=99t w=
ant to compete with them directly.=C2=A0
Doing the hardest and least lucrative bookings, we developed a unique set o=
f strengths. Our operations team could turn a space in 30 minutes. Our data=
 science team could dynamically price spaces based on real-time demand sign=
als. Our design, construction, and launch teams were used to high-volume, s=
hort timeline space launches. Users booked through an app, on-demand, and a=
ccessed the space with their phone. They used spaces for a number of differ=
ent use cases =E2=80=93 meetings, brainstorms, focused work, events =E2=80=
=93 often requiring different configurations. We coordinated everything thr=
ough our in-house backend system.=C2=A0
Based on those strengths, and the clear margin challenge, we identified a c=
ouple of core challenges to focus on.=C2=A0
We needed to fill our space inventory more consistently to improve margins.=
=C2=A0
We could move upmarket into monthly bookings much more easily than WeWork a=
nd Knotel could move downmarket into private, on-demand hourly bookings.=C2=
=A0
We might be able to counter-position to buy ourselves time to create switch=
ing costs.=C2=A0
With that diagnosis in-hand, we set out a guiding policy.=C2=A0
Guiding Policy
Our guiding policy was simple: offer growing startups a network of flexible=
 spaces that grows with their needs instead of one single office. To do tha=
t, we would make every space in our network available for as little as an h=
our and as long as a year, priced in real-time based on demand.=C2=A0
If a space was underperforming as an hourly space, we could make it availab=
le as a monthly office for a lower price than our competitors: turning a sp=
ace from negative to breakeven improved the network=E2=80=99s margins, and =
pushed its demand into nearby strong-performing hourly spaces, juicing thei=
r margins. If a customer rented a space for a month+, we could offer them d=
iscounts on nearby spaces, allowing them to spend less on a permanent space=
 and flex up when they needed more room to host an important meeting, have =
a sensitive conversation, or a place to work when they traveled to another =
one of our markets.=C2=A0
Instead of viewing each space independently, we viewed the whole network as=
 one big office that responded to our customers=E2=80=99 needs on-demand.=
=C2=A0
Coherent Actions
Actually pulling that off was insanely difficult and required intense execu=
tion from the team.=C2=A0
As just a few examples, we needed to:=C2=A0
Update our pricing models to dynamically price spaces both hourly and month=
ly.=C2=A0
Retrain our BD team to sell monthly spaces and trust the data science team=
=E2=80=99s pricing when selling, and re-orient their quotas around month+ s=
ales targets.=C2=A0
Update our website and app to enable both hourly and monthly bookings on th=
e frontend, with live prices and availability updated hourly.=C2=A0
Redo our backend system - Backstage - to account for both hourly and monthl=
y bookings.
Design spaces that could be flipped between hourly and monthly bookings wit=
hin a day to minimize dead time, and rework our launch and logistics proces=
ses to transform spaces in that day.=C2=A0
Source new furniture from overseas and design some of our own to facilitate=
 that switching.=C2=A0
Retrain our operations team to clean and maintain both hourly and monthly b=
ookings. After an hourly booking, a space needs a full reset; when it=E2=80=
=99s someone=E2=80=99s office, they want it to be clean but they want their=
 things exactly where they left them.=C2=A0
Use our pricing models to inform the real estate team=E2=80=99s new space a=
cquisitions. Because of our mix of bookings and the on-demand nature, we ha=
d the most real-time commercial real estate pricing data, and used it to in=
form an underwriting model that predicted a space=E2=80=99s revenue to 95%+=
 accuracy.=C2=A0
Lease larger spaces, and cluster more spaces near each other to give month+=
 customers convenient access to different space types when they needed.=C2=
=A0
Change the way that access codes worked so that monthly clients didn=E2=80=
=99t need to inform their teams of a new code every day.=C2=A0
Train our customer care team to work differently with hourly and monthly cl=
ients.=C2=A0
Update our marketing to reflect our new value proposition, and to create le=
ads for the sales team instead of driving everything to in-app on-demand bo=
okings.=C2=A0
Each one of these actions alone, or in the hands of competitors, wouldn=E2=
=80=99t have done much good. Together, they built a machine that had a mome=
ntum of its own.=C2=A0
There were a thousand more things that the team did to put the new strategy=
 into action, but that gives you a flavor. Half the battle was being clear =
about what we were trying to do, and why, and pointing out that we were the=
 only ones who could do it. The vast majority of the coherent actions that =
the team took didn=E2=80=99t come from Ben and I; they came from the team.=
=C2=A0
That year was the most exhilarating of my six at Breather. We moved so fast=
=2E People stayed at the office late an=
d cheered every time a gong ring annou=
nced a monthly booking.=C2=A0
And it worked. Our margins flipped from -25% to +25% in six months. WeWork =
and Knotel didn=E2=80=99t respond, and we were able to steal customers from=
 them. They were still much bigger than us, but we offered something unique=
=2E=C2=A0
Unfortunately, we didn=E2=80=99t get the chance to see whether the strategy=
 would have created long-term defensibility. We threw it out when the new e=
xec team joined in 2019, focusing solely on plain vanilla monthly bookings.=
 Who knows if our strategy would have been enough to overcome the headwinds=
 in a brutal market, or if we could have raised enough money to continue co=
mpeting.=C2=A0
Breather may have failed even if we had kept executing this strategy. It wa=
s a competitive market and our competitors were willing to spend like drunk=
en sailors. Good strategy, even paired with strong execution, isn=E2=80=99t=
 a guarantee of success.=C2=A0
But strong execution without a good strategy is a road to nowhere in an F1 =
car.=C2=A0
Don=E2=80=99t ignore strategy. Read Good Strategy Bad Strategy [ https://li=
nk.sbstck.com/redirect/46f2f7e2-b9e8-4135-98a1-4a30a8d16b69?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], 7 Powers [ https://l=
ink.sbstck.com/redirect/2a10f313-693f-439e-a057-28aaff0bf701?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOX=
AwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU ], and Productive Unce=
rtainty [ https://reactionwheel.net/2020/11/productive-uncertainty.html ]. =
Take the time to honestly diagnose the situation, come up with a good guidi=
ng policy, and focus your company=E2=80=99s limited actions so that they bu=
ild on each other. Keep refreshing it as you learn more. Have fun solving t=
he puzzle.=C2=A0
Running a startup is going to be hard no matter what. Execution is hard. So=
 don't just execute. Plot a course, forge advantages, build strengths. Crea=
te something enduring.
Strategy comes down to choices. The first choice is whether or not to have =
a strategy. Founders can bet on brute force execution alone. Or pair execut=
ion with strategy to tilt the odds.
When uncertainty looms, strategy lets you see the path before competitors d=
o. It might just give you the time you need to succeed.=20
