and Google, and ChatGPT) for examples of startups that have achieved $10 bi=
llion+ outcomes </span><em>without</em><span> a good strategy, </span><em>w=
ithout</em><span> moats in place by the time their success became obvious, =
and I just can&#8217;t come up with any.&#160;&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"=
color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20p=
x 0;"><span>If startups need to dig moats before their uncertainty runs out=
, strategy is how they do it. </span><strong>If moats are the what, strateg=
y is the how.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Every startup has a windo=
w of time during which they must simultaneously build something worth defen=
ding and build defenses around it.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, =
64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>For new=
 startups, strategy is deciding how to use the window wisely. It&#8217;s ab=
out </span><strong>directing your limited resources towards digging moats b=
efore you&#8217;ve removed enough uncertainty to attract serious competitio=
n.</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-he=
ight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Like moats, strategy is often thought of a=
s something that bigger companies need to worry about, when they have to co=
ordinate thousands of people and defend against dozens of competitors. Most=
 of the strategy literature is written for those bigger companies, and most=
 of it is overkill for startups.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64=
); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>That does=
n&#8217;t mean that strategy is more important for big companies than for s=
tartups. The opposite is true: </span><strong>strategy is highest-leverage =
at Day 0</strong><span>, when all paths are available.&#160;</span></p><div=
 class=3D"captioned-image-container-static" style=3D"font-size: 16px; line-=
