pKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: =
underline;">Crux</a></em><span> in a new book &#8211; but bad strategy danc=
es around it in favor of a bunch of things that matter less but are easier =
to deal with or measure.&#160;</span></p></li><li style=3D"margin: 8px 0 0 =
32px; mso-special-format: bullet;"><p style=3D"box-sizing: border-box; colo=
r: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0; margin-b=
ottom: 0; padding-left: 4px;"><strong>Ignoring Competition</strong><span>: =
Companies exist in dynamic markets; a failure to recognize competition or a=
nticipate their response to your moves is lazy and dangerous.&#160;</span><=
/p></li></ul><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heig=
ht: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Before Breather eventually fell victim=
 to bad strategy, Ben and I came up with a </span><em>good</em><span> strat=
egy (if I do say so myself). I&#8217;ll explain it once we&#8217;ve covered=
 </span><strong>good strategy</strong><span>, but for now, I&#8217;ll say t=
hat our gross margins improved from -25% to +25% in six months by doing som=
ething competitors couldn&#8217;t easily match.&#160;</span></p><p style=3D=
"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20=
px 0;">Then we brought in a new CEO, who brought in a new exec team, in 201=
9. A couple weeks into their tenure, Ben and I presented our strategy at an=
