/p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; =
margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>&#8220;Why? Why do we need a strategy? This is=
 a big market, we don&#8217;t need to worry about moats. We have a brand. T=
hat&#8217;s what Apple has. Our space plan model is the strategy.&#8221;&#1=
60;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Mistaking a Goal (the space plan model) f=
or Strategy: &#9989;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px=
; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Failure to Face the Challenge: &#=
9989;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: =
26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Ignoring Competition: &#9989;</p><p style=3D"col=
or: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0=
;">Thinking a Good Brand is a Brand Moat: not in the book, but a common mis=
take &#9989;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Comparing Your Company to Apple: lol&#160=
;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">All that bad strategy in 34 words! Impressive!&#160;=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Doing Bad Strategy and calling it Strategy give=
s the whole thing a bad name, and scares people away from the simple and ne=
cessary work of crafting a </span><strong>Good Strategy</strong><span>.</sp=
an></p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widget" style=3D"-moz-appearance: op=
timizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: antialiased; -webkit-appearance:=
 optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing: antialiased; appearance: optim=
izelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-family: 'SF Compact Display', -=
apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI', Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, san=
s-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoji', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-siz=
e: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: 1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0=
; position: relative;"><strong>Good Startup Strategy</strong></h3><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">Rumelt doesn&#8217;t give a one-sentence definition of strategy i=
n the book, but if he did, it would look something like this:&#160;</p><p s=
tyle=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin:=
 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>A strategy is a high-level plan to achieve one or mor=
e goals under conditions of uncertainty, designed through recognizing the c=
hallenge (diagnosis), setting a direction to overcome it (guiding policy), =
and detailing steps to implement the policy (coherent actions).</strong><sp=
an>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; li=
ne-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Those three pieces &#8212; diag=
nosis, guiding policy, and coherent actions &#8212; form the strategy kerne=
l. By combining the strategy kernel with what we discussed in </span><em><a=
 href=3D"https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/7d6cba49-0489-4d74-af64-2f5664614=
fce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel=
 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">When to Dig =
a Moat</a><span>,</span></em><span> we can come up with something a little =
more tailored to early stage startups.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=
 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A startu=
p can&#8217;t be expected to have moats in the early days, but it should ha=
ve a strategy in place that gives it the best chance of having them in plac=
e by the time the uncertainty window runs out.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: =
rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">T=
he best time to craft a strategy is before you start the company; the secon=
d best time is now.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size:=
 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Strategy isn&#8217;t set in =
stone. It should evolve as the facts do, and as the startup learns by doing=
=2E A startup&#8217;s strategy should a=
ctually evolve faster than a larger co=
mpany&#8217;s because there&#8217;s so much uncertainty and such a high rat=
e of learning, and because a startup is still nimble enough to change cours=
e as needed.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; =
line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>A rough way of thinking about=
 </span><em>what</em><span> should change is that the diagnosis should be t=
he most stable, the guiding policy should be relatively stable, and the coh=
erent actions should be the quickest to adapt to new information. Let&#8217=
;s take each in turn.&#160;</span></p><h3 class=3D"header-with-anchor-widge=
t" style=3D"-moz-appearance: optimizelegibility; -moz-osx-font-smoothing: a=
ntialiased; -webkit-appearance: optimizelegibility; -webkit-font-smoothing:=
 antialiased; appearance: optimizelegibility; color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-=
family: 'SF Compact Display', -apple-system, BlinkMacSystemFont, 'Segoe UI'=
, Roboto, Helvetica, Arial, sans-serif, 'Apple Color Emoji', 'Segoe UI Emoj=
i', 'Segoe UI Symbol'; font-size: 1.375em; font-weight: bold; line-height: =
1.16em; margin: 1em 0 0.625em 0; position: relative;"><strong>Diagnosis</st=
rong></h3><blockquote style=3D"border-left: 4px solid #51b4e9; margin: 20px=
 0; padding: 0;"><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-=
height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0; margin-left: 20px;"><em>At a minimum, a d=
iagnosis names or classifies the situation, linking facts into patterns and=
 suggesting more attention be paid to some issues and less to others.</em><=
/p></blockquote><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-h=
eight: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">A good diagnosis is the most important pi=
ece of the strategy kernel for a startup. Getting it right is the highest l=
everage thing you can do, so we&#8217;ll spend most of our time here.&#160;=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Every founder does some form of diagnosis before star=
ting a company. They survey the landscape of available products and unmet c=
ustomer needs, and evaluate their own abilities and the inputs available to=
 build a better solution.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font=
-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">This shows up in pitch=
 decks as the &#8220;Problem&#8221; and &#8220;Solution&#8221; slides, and =
in investor conversations as the answer to &#8220;Why now?&#8221;&#160;</p>=
<p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; mar=
gin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>My brother Dan started </span><a href=3D"https://li=
nk.sbstck.com/redirect/821d8366-96df-4b4e-b1c6-fee93248cb7f?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXA=
wZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rg=
b(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Create</a><span> because he not=
iced a wide gap between the public perception of creatine and the very posi=
tive research on its effectiveness, realized that well-branded gummies woul=
d be a more palatable form factor than powders for most consumers, and reco=
gnized that his experience at Away, Parade, and Not Boring gave him the rig=
ht skillset to build the brand. A little over six months in, he&#8217;s at =
a $6 million run rate. It seems to have been a good diagnosis.&#160;</span>=
</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px;=
 margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Most startups stop there, but a good startup diagnosi=
s needs to go further.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-si=
ze: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>First, startups n=
eed to honestly assess how obvious their product is and how hard it is to b=
uild.</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); fo=
nt-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>This is what w=
e talked about in </span><em><a href=3D"https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/7d=
6cba49-0489-4d74-af64-2f5664614fce?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaM=
ZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decor=
ation: underline;">When to Dig a Moat</a><span>.</span></em><span> Estimate=
 a starting uncertainty window, a rough guide for how soon you&#8217;ll fac=
e competition, how quickly you&#8217;ll need to dig moats, and how deep the=
y&#8217;ll need to be.</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Because the uncertainty =
window depends on the progress a company makes, it&#8217;s more useful to t=
hink about this in terms of milestones than time: &#8220;By the time we&#82=
17;ve proven X, competitors are likely to attack.&#8221; That&#8217;s when =
you should have early moats in place.&#160;</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 6=
4, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><strong>Th=
en, startups need to understand which moats, which of Hamilton Helmer&#8217=
;s </strong><em><strong><a href=3D"https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2a10f31=
3-693f-439e-a057-28aaff0bf701?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlX=
XepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration=
: underline;">7 Powers</a></strong></em><strong>, are available in the mark=
et they&#8217;re attacking.&#160;</strong></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64=
, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Picking the=
 right moat for your market is crucial.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 6=
4); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>As </spa=
n><a href=3D"https://link.sbstck.com/redirect/2c98c9ff-976c-47e3-83a6-d52a8=
b776798?j=3DeyJ1IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU"=
 rel style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Dan Hock=
enmaier</a><span>, who runs strategy and analytics at </span><a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.sbstck.com/redirect/1df8a237-aae7-47a5-a060-9bb1dacce5ee?j=3DeyJ1=
IjoiOXAwZ3QifQ.gb8J5T7GnA_ZlNuaMZjmlXXepKbqOsa8-6m8ExkRNpU" rel style=3D"co=
lor: rgb(64, 64, 64); text-decoration: underline;">Faire</a><span> put it: =
</span><strong>&#8220;Most of the value is picking a lane that&#8217;s goin=
g to lend itself to defensibility.&#8221;</strong><span>&#160;</span></p><p=
 style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margi=
n: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>If you&#8217;re building a physical product, you migh=
t focus on </span><strong>scale economies</strong><span>. If you&#8217;re b=
uilding a SaaS product, you might focus on </span><strong>switching costs</=
strong><span>. If you&#8217;re building a social app, you&#8217;ll probably=
 focus on </span><strong>network effects</strong><span>.</span></p><p style=
=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0=
 20px 0;">It&#8217;s important to be a student of history here. Optimism is=
 an important trait in a founder, but realism skewing towards pessimism is =
the right state of mind for a diagnosis. The first moat you reach for might=
 not survive deeper scrutiny.</p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-s=
ize: 16px; line-height: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Take social apps. =
Understand why the last 1,000 failed before convincing yourself you&#8217;l=
l be the one to crack </span><strong>network effects</strong><span>. </span=
></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64, 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-height: 26px=
; margin: 0 0 20px 0;"><span>Or marketplaces. Hockenmaier notes that, &#822=
0;</span><strong>Network effects</strong><span> are overrated for marketpla=
ces. They are usually not enough to drive defensibility on their own. They =
take too many lessons from single-sided network effects and ignore the chal=
lenges with dual-sided networks.&#8221; Look instead to </span><strong>scal=
e economies</strong><span> or </span><strong>switching costs</strong><span>=
=2E</span></p><p style=3D"color: rgb(64,=
 64, 64); font-size: 16px; line-heigh=
t: 26px; margin: 0 0 20px 0;">Aim for moats with non-linear returns, where =
being 2x or 10x bigger provides outsized benefits. Hockenmaier looks for &#=
8220;asymptoting curves that take a long time to asymptote.&#8221; The goal=
 is finding moats where you stay steps ahead thanks to non-linear returns.&=
